cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we'll continue our look at the Precision 1@H & 1@S Openings & Responses. 

Last week we covered Mini-splinters, Splinters and fit-showing Jump-Shift responses. This week we'll be looking at Romex Trial Bids. If you have not already done so, please have a look at the notes I have prepared on Precision Club bidding. 

You can find these on: ^*hhttp://ocp.pigpen.org.uk^*n  You might want to have these onscreen in the background for reference during the session. The notes on Romex can be found on the 1@H and 1@S pages.

Even if you have no interest in Precision, please stick around Romex can be applied to ANY bidding system, and if you want to sharpen up your Major Suit sequences, this is the session for you.  

Firstly, a brief recap of what we covered last week:
| 
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


qx|Spln,wide|
nt|^b@2^z@3|
at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Re-cap       Splinter  Responses     to     1@h   and  1@s   Openings|fp||at|

Splinters are a double jump-shift over an Opening bid of 1@H or 1@S. They absolutely agree Opener's Major, show a strong (ostensibly 16+) hand with GOOD controls and also show a shortage.

They show a hand strongly interested in more than a game contract.  In most systems you splinter in your SHORT suit, so 1@S-4@C would show a Club shortage. This is NOT the method recommended or used in this system. 

Instead we splinter in the suit BELOW our shortage, ignoring the agreed trump suit and NT's. Thus 1@S-4@C shows a DIAMOND shortage amd 1@S-4@H would show a CLUB shortage. 

This is primarily to facilitate a cheap control Asking Bid (Beta) in responder's short suit and this method of showing a shortage is fairly consistent throughout this system.
|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  In practice, as I said last week, we actually use splinters VERY RARELY immediately over an opening of 1@H or 1@S. The reason for this is that we have a very much more space-efficient way of exploring for slam that leaves Responder in control of the auction rather than Opener, who is limited.

More of that later in the series once we've covered the Asking Bids. 

Next we dealt with Mini-Splinters and Fit-showing Jump-shifts.   Most systems use jump-shift responses to show a game-forcing hand of some sort.  Some pairs play jump-shifts as weak. 
|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


qx|FSJS,wide|
at|^^^^^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Re-cap     Fit Showing Jump Shift (FSJS)       responses   to   1@h   and  1@s   Openings|fp||at|

This system plays jump-shifts over 1@H and 1@S as being mildly invitational in Opener's Major, along these lines.

Jump-shifts in a SUIT (with one exception - see below) show about 8-9 points, reasonable 3+-card trump support for Opener's Major and a 5-card or longer side-suit that can be expected to be a source of tricks (eg: something like AQxxx rather than Q86xx. 

So 1@H-3@C would show a reasonably good Club suit, some Heart support and about 8-9 HCP The exception mentioned above relates to Spades. 1@H-2NT is used to show a fit-showing jump-shift in Spades. 

This is because 1@H-2@S is required for a different purpose (Mini-splinters below). 

These fit-showing jump-shifts are NOT forcing but they do agree Opener's Major and are aimed at getting to thin (sub-minimum) games if Opener is Maximum and/or has a suitable fit for Responder's side-suit. 
|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


qx|Mini,wide|
nt|^z@3^b@2|
at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Re-cap     Mini-Splinter      responses    to   1@h   and  1@s   Openings|fp||at|

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Next came mini-splinters  1@S - 2NT  and  1@H - 2@S  are used to show Mini-Splinters. These also show about 8-9 points and decent 4-card or longer support for Opener's Major. 

They show a shortage in an UNSPECIFIED suit. 

Opener can sign off at any level in their Major if not interested in knowing where the shortage is or can relay in the next bid up.  

For example  1@H-2@S-2NT,  1@S-2NT-3@C  to enquire about the location of the shortage if that makes a difference, bear in mind that that information can be useful to the Opponent on the Opening lead.

If Opener asks for the location of the short suit, Responder bids the suit BELOW their shortage in a sort of rotating wheel ignoring the trump suit @-|
