As with fit-showing jump-shifts, Mini-Splinters are aimed at getting to thin games based mainly on fit rather than a solid point-count. If mid-range, Opener will judge whether the hands are likely to be fitting well given their holding in the mini-splinter suit.  

So xxx(x) or perhaps Axx(x) is an ideal holding whereas KJx(x), KQx(x) or x tends not to be indicative of a good fit.
|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Trial Bids    Use and Purpose (background)|fp||at|

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Let's move on to Trial Bids. In case any of you are not familiar with the concept of trial bids let's cover that general ground (only because there are lots of people who have misconceptions about them)  first @-

Trial bids generally occur ANY time we've explicitly agreed a Major suit at the 2-level and the original bidder of the suit has a hand worth an invitation. 

This doesn't have to be an immediate agreement like 1@H - 2@H, but might be something like     1@H - 1NT - 2@C - 2@H, 
or     1@H - 1@S - 2@S    or even     1@D - 1@H - 1@S - 2@S     or     1@D - 1@S - 2@S. 

Trial bids are an invitation to game in the agreed Major suit. Instead of simply raising the major to the 3-level (which is somewhat uninformative) the player making the trial bid is showing something else about their hand. 

This is intended to give partner some clue as to what to do ONLY if they are mid-range and undecided as to whether or not to accept the invitation. 

With a minimum hand partner is expected to sign off in the Major at the 3-level and to go to game with a maximum. 

It is the nebulous middle ground when you're not sure whether to treat your hand as lower or upper range that trial bids help with. There are normally 2 possible kinds of trial bids over a Major @-
|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


at|
^c(1)^d@2Most systems use LONG-suit (AKA "Help suit") Trial Bids. Using this method the trial-bidder is showing a 3-card or longer suit and are looking for partner to have a shortage or some honour strength in that suit. So a singleton or void is helpful, as is a holding such as Ax(x) or Kx(x).
|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|
^c@2(2)^d@2Classic Precision uses a different method: Short-suit Trial Bids are where the Trial-bidder shows a shortage (singleton or void) and is now looking for partner to have NO wasted values in that suit if they are mid-range (eg: xxx(x) is fine and Axx(x) is also okay, but a holding like KJx(x) or KQx(x) is not so good) as you are less likely to get full value from those honours opposite a singleton or void.
|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Most systems tend to use Long-suit trial bids because they give less information away to opponents. A long-suit trial bids might be anything from xxx up to AKxxx, whereas a short-suit trial bid is always going to be a singleton or void, making it much easier for the defence to count the hand.

Classic Precision's use of short-suit trial bids owes much to the fact that  1M - 2M  sequences are largely pre-emptive rather than being limit bids as such.  Trial Bids, therefore, are a more scientific way of raising the agreed Major to the 3-level as an invitation to game.


|fp|t-title|at|Romex Trial Bids|fp||at|

The problem is that normally you have to agree whether to play long or short trial bids before you start and have to stick with that decision.  You cannot normally play both methods at the same time but Romex is a method to permit you to do exactly that.
 
Romex allows you to play both long and short-suit trials bids and to choose which method to use on any given hand to give partner the most help in making their decision. 
 
The way it achieves this is fairly ingenious (similar in many ways to the concept behind Lebensohl) and it also gives the additional benefit that you only actually get to MAKE a SHORT-suit trial bid when it really matters to partner (which is really good, because, as I said before, short-suit trial bids tend to give more info to Opps). 

^c"How can you possibly tell whether or not it really matters to partner?" 

I hear you ask. Well I'll leave you in suspense for a short while as we'll cover long-suit trials first.

Using Romex, Long-suit trial bids are, with one exception, identical to long-suit trial bids in any other system.
|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


qx|LSTB_m,wide|
nt|^z@3^b@2|
at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Romex Long Suit Trial Bids|fp||
at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  For example  

^c 1@D - 1@H - 2@H - 3@D    is a long-suit trial bid in Diamonds 

^c 1@D - 1@S - 2@S - 3@H    is a long-suit trial bid in Hearts  

Opener bids game with a maximum 14-15 and signs off at the 3-level with a minimum 11-12. 

With a good 12 up to a poor 14-count, they let their holding in the trial suit decide. The exception to this, as with fit-showing jump-shifts, relates to SPADES.


To make a long-suit trial bid in SPADES if Hearts are agreed at the 2-level you bid 2NT rather than 2@S. 

So using Romex Trial Bids   

^c 1@H - 2@H - 2NT   is a long-suit trial bid in  @sSPADES@s

^c 1@H - 2@H - 2@S     is something else (see later). 

All other long-suit trial bids are exactly as you would find them in any other system.

