Bear in mind that it's always the player who is going to be Declarer who makes the trial bid.

To ask you where the shortage is, partner simply relays in the next suit up over the Romex Bid.  Thus 1@H - 2@H - 2@S - 2NT and 1@S - 2@S - 2NT - 3@C are each saying "Ok, where is your shortage?".

Now the trial bidder bids the suit BELOW their shortage (the scheme is identical to that for Mini-Splinters, as it happens). Thus:

^e1@H - 2@H - 2@S - 2NT - 3@C   shows  a   Diamond     ^pshortage
^e1@H - 2@H - 2@S - 2NT - 3@D   shows  a   Spade       ^pshortage
^e1@H - 2@H - 2@S - 2NT - 3@H   shows  a   @CCLUB@C    ^pshortage
              
^e1@S - 2@S - 2NT - 3@C - 3@D   shows  a   Heart       ^pshortage
^e1@S - 2@S - 2NT - 3@C - 3@H   shows  a   @CCLUB@C    ^pshortage
^e1@S - 2@S - 2NT - 3@C - 3@S   shows  a   @DDIAMOND@D ^pshortage

Although it is extremely unlikely that you would ever want to use the short-suit as a control asking bid in this kind of sequence, we use the suit-below method for consistency with the rest of this system.

If you are not playing Precision then you can happily just bid the short suit itself rather than the suit below (but even there you may need to make some adjustments when the shortage is in a Minor.

Either way, you cannot afford for your response to go PAST 3 of the agreed Major, otherwise you're committed to game regardless.
