at|^^^^|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The ONLY time it is defensible to have a sequence such as that is when the Trial Bid is actually a "slam trial bid".

The Trial bid itself is, of course, 100% forcing so Responder, in this instance, can make a cheap slam try IN THE GUISE of a Trial Bid. 

Take the following hand:  You hold @SAK107xx, @Hx, @DAKJ10x, @Cx and partner opens 1@H. Over your 1@S response, partner bids 2@S.
 
Now what?  4@D would be a Splinter in @H, for Spades, but a shortage in @H is not likely to set partner on fire. 

Similarly a 4@H bid, ostensibly showing the Club shortage, might be misunderstood for a Delayed Game Raise in Hearts (it is an ambiguous sequence).

3@D, however, is bombproof. If Opener is lower range or if they nothing helpful in Diamonds, they will bid 3@S and now you sign off in game. 

If, however, Opener is Upper Range, or mid-range with a helpful holding in Diamonds, they will bid 4@S and now 4NT from you can only be an invitation to cue-bid (specifically looking for the Ace of Clubs with partner, or you'd bid 5@C yourself) which will make everything clearer. 

Situations like these will, for practical purposes, always be ones where it is Responder's suit that Opener has agreed, and Responder (whose hand will not be limited in any way) is making the invitation. 

If Responder has agreed Opener's suit by making only a 2-level raise, then it is inconceivable that Opener (who has already limited their hand by their choice of Opening) has enough to invite slam rather than game (assuming you're playing Precision, of course). 
