at|^^^^|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  If you're playing 2/1 or Standard American, of course, Opener might well be strong enough.

Romex therefore achieves the seemingly impossible and gives additional advantages in that we only give information to Opp's when it is more important to US to decide at what level to play.

On many hands you will find that you could potentially make either a short-suit or a long-suit trial bid.

On these occasions you have to think about what you want partner to have in the trial suit, but normally long-suit trial bids give less away and should be preferred.

For example, suppose you hold   @SAQxxx  @HAxxx  @Dx  @CAxx     You open 1@S and partner raises to 2@S.

Do you make a long-suit trial bid in Hearts or Clubs or ask to make a short-suit trial bid and then show your Diamond shortage?

On the kind of hand where you have good control of the other side-suits, I would prefer a short-suit trial bid in Diamonds.

But if the hand was more like    @SAKQTxx   @HJ10xx   @Dx   @CAx   I would definitely make a long-suit trial bid in Hearts rather than a short-suit trial in Diamonds.

